{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e218e71-a964-484c-87c7-a16f21786908","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues I found:\n\n## Performance Problems\n\n### 1. Deeply Chained Imports (3 levels)\n`EvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props`\n\nEach import adds file I/O and XML parsing during evaluation. Deeply nested chains multiply the cost and make caching less effective.\n\n### 2. Expensive Glob Pattern (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThe recursive wildcard `**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to enumerate the **entire directory tree** on every evaluation. This scales poorly as the repo grows.\n\n### 3. File I/O via Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File::ReadAllText` during evaluation performs synchronous disk I/O in the critical path. This bypasses MSBuild's caching and is re-executed on every evaluation pass.\n\n## Recommendations\n| Issue | Fix |\n|-------|-----|\n| Nested imports | Flatten into a single `.props` or reduce depth |\n| Broad glob | Narrow the pattern to specific extensions/directories |\n| `ReadAllText` in property | Move to a target that runs at build-time, or use a static item instead |\n\nThe `ReadAllText` call and the `**\\*.*` glob are the most impactful — they turn every IDE keystroke (which triggers re-evaluation) into expensive disk operations.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"027562ba-c3d3-4f52-86cd-2fd7a2013e51","outputTokens":394,"requestId":"F01C:21DC3D:26F9F21:2B3EA60:69F94590"},"id":"e626c109-7b07-4956-afd4-830a86a6fcb3","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:19:21.769Z","parentId":"00968ae1-ce56-417f-8e3e-156825527ced"}
